category=Getting Started
description=<p>This example shows you how to bring a window to the front when the user chooses from a menu containing a list of open windows  <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><b>Note:</b></font> see the example &quot;Updating a menu with a list of open Windows&quot; for a script that populates the menu with a list of currently open windows. </p>
discussion=<p>The <font face="Courier" size="11">menuPick</font> message is sent when the user chooses a menu item from the menu. Remember that in Revolution, menus are usually implemented as buttons:  the button's <font face="Courier" size="11">style</font> and <font face="Courier" size="11">menuMode</font> properties control how it is displayed, and the button's <font face="Courier" size="11">text</font> property is used as the list of menu items. When the <font face="Courier" size="11">menuPick</font> message is sent to the button, it triggers this handler.  For more details on how to create a menu bar, see the section on <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>Building a User Interface</i></font> in the <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>User's Guide</i></font>, and for scripting menus see the section on <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>Scripting Menus and the Menu Bar</i></font> in the <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>User's Guide</i></font>.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>In the <font face="Courier" size="11">mouseDown</font> handler described in &quot;Updating a menu with a list of open Windows&quot;, we placed the title of each open stack in the <font face="Courier" size="11">menu</font>, and set a custom property called &quot;currentStacksList&quot; containing the corresponding stack names. If that <font face="Courier" size="11">mouseDown</font> handler is in the menu button's script (or the script of the menu bar group that contains the button), the property has already been set when the user clicked the menu, so it's ready when our <font face="Courier" size="11">menuPick</font> handler is executed. This property is needed because the menu displays titles, not the actual stack names; the &quot;currentStacksList&quot; property lets us figure out the name corresponding to the stack label the user chose.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The <font face="Courier" size="11">menuHistory</font> property of a button <font face="Courier" size="11">menu</font> is the number of the last-chosen menu item. Each line of the button contents becomes a separate menu item when the menu is displayed, so the <font face="Courier" size="11">menuHistory</font> is also the line number of the menu item.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The <font face="Courier" size="11">menuPick</font> handler also gets the text of the chosen menu item as a parameter. However, in this example, we don't really care what the text of the chosen menu item is: it's a stack <font face="Courier" size="11">title</font>, and you can't specify a stack by its <font face="Courier" size="11">title</font> in order to bring it to the front. Instead, we need the stack <font face="Courier" size="11">name</font> stored in the button's &quot;currentStacksList&quot; custom property.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The names were stored in the &quot;currentStacksList&quot; property in the same order as the labels in the menu itself, so if we know the menu item's number, and get that line number of the &quot;currentStacksList&quot; property, we have the <font face="Courier" size="11">name</font> of the stack. The <font face="Courier" size="11">menuHistory</font> gives us this number.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Once we've retrieved the stack's name from the &quot;currentStacksList&quot; property, we use the <font face="Courier" size="11">go</font> command to bring the stack window to the front. If there is some problem and the <font face="Courier" size="11">go</font> command can't find the stack, it sets the <font face="Courier" size="11">result</font> function to empty. The last thing we do is check the result, and <font face="Courier" size="11">beep</font> if it's not empty.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font color="#404040"><img src="202651"> </font><font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><b>Tip:</b></font> The &quot;currentStacksList&quot; custom property is needed because the Window menu displays a list of the titles of open stacks instead of their names, for better readability, but you need the name--not the label--to refer to a stack. There's a simpler way to do this, if you don't mind displaying the name of each stack instead of its label in the Window menu. If the Window menu consists of a list of stack names, a handler to choose one of them looks like this:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">on</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> menuPick theStackName</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">    </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">go</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> stack theStackName</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">end</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> menuPick</font></p>
level=2
licensed=false
name=Responding to a choice in a Window menu
solution=<p><font color="#980517">on</font> menuPick <font color="#68228B">-- goes in the menu button script</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#68228B">-- This handler assumes the button has a custom property</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#68228B">-- named &quot;stackNamesList&quot; that contains the names of</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#68228B">-- the stacks listed in the menu</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">put</font> line (the <font color="#FF0000">menuHistory</font> of <font color="#F88017">me</font>) \\</p>\n<p>     of the currentStacksList of <font color="#F88017">me</font> into chosenStackName</p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">go</font> stack chosenStackName</p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">if</font> the <font color="#F88017">result</font> is not empty <font color="#980517">then</font> <font color="#0000FF">beep</font> <font color="#68228B">-- couldn't find stack</font></p>\n<p><font color="#980517">end</font> menuPick </p>
title=Responding to a choice in a Window menu